      {
        "id": 2434507,
        "name": "Luis Manuel Debuque Monreal Ermita\u00f1o",
        "username": "LMD_Ermitano",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/lmd_ermitano/{size}/77101_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-06-19T07:56:56.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I should have mentioned that I was referring to Tribut\u2019s village Chablis, which is what I usually have when having simply prepared seafood (fresh oysters, steamed crab, etc.). Minimal/old oak, no b\u00e2ttonage, etc. His Beauroy and C\u00f4te de L\u00e9chet (the only other two of his lines imported in Manila) are quite different.</p>\n<p>I, myself, suspected the '12 Raveneau Monts Mains was too young; but, well, it was the one I saw on the restaurant\u2019s wine list that I wanted. Even at a 1* Michelin, in Kilkenny, Ireland, fine wine lists are not the best. One works with what one is presented at the time.</p>",
